  <content>
<para id="para-00001">We saw in <link document="m00224"/> that certain nucleophiles, such as amines, react with <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated aldehydes and ketones to give a conjugate addition product, rather than a direct addition product.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reversible chemical reaction of a carbonyl compound in the presence of a nucleophile amine (blue) to yield an intermediate product which undergoes a reversible reaction to yield a conjugate addition product. The structure of the carbonyl compound shows a radical bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a carbon atom having an open bond and double bonded (pink) to a carbon atom having 2 open bonds. A pink arrow is shows from: the lone pair of electrons from the nucleophile to the third carbon atom in the reactant; and from the double bond between the carbon atoms to the second carbon atom. The structure of the intermediate shows a radical group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a carbon anion with a lone pair of electrons having an open bond and bonded to a carbon atom having 2 open bonds and bonded to a blue nucleophile bonded to a blue hydrogen atom. The structure of the conjugate addition product shows a radical group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a carbon atom having an open bond a blue hydrogen and a carbon atom having 2 open bonds and a blue nucleophile.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_23_10_001.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00002">Exactly the same kind of conjugate addition can occur when a nucleophilic enolate ion reacts with an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated carbonyl compound—a process known as the <term id="term-00001">Michael reaction</term> after Arthur Michael at Tufts College and Harvard University.</para>
<para id="para-00003">The best Michael reactions are those that take place when a particularly stable enolate ion, such as that derived from a <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-keto ester or other 1,3-dicarbonyl compound, adds to an unhindered <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated ketone. For example, ethyl acetoacetate reacts with 3-buten-2-one in the presence of sodium ethoxide to yield the conjugate addition product.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00002">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction where ethyl acetoacetate combines with 3-Buten-2-one in the presence of sodium ethoxide ethanol and hydronium ion to yield a conjugate addition product. The structure of ethyl acetoacetate shows a methyl group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group (blue hydrogen) bonded to pink COOEt. The structure of 3-Buten-2-one shows a methylene group double bonded (blue) to a methine group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group. The structure of the conjugate addition product shows a methyl group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a carbon bonded to a blue hydrogen pink COOEt and bonded (pink) to a methylene group bonded to a methylene group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_23_10_002.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00004">Michael reactions take place by addition of a nucleophilic enolate ion donor to the <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis> carbon of an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated carbonyl acceptor, according to the mechanism shown in <link target-id="fig-00003"/>.</para>
<figure class="mechanism-figure scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
<title>MECHANISM</title>
<media alt="An illustration shows the 3 steps of the Michael reaction between a beta keto ester and an alpha beta-unsaturated ketone. The structure shown in step 1 shows a pink carbonyl group bonded (pink) to a pink ethoxide and a carbon atom bonded to 2 blue hydrogen and a carbonyl group (with a pink oxygen atom) bonded to a methyl group. This undergoes a reversible chemical reaction in the presence of blue sodium ethoxide. The supporting text in step 1 reads “The base catalyst removes an acidic alpha proton from the starting beta keto ester to generate a stabilized enolate ion nucleophile.” The structure of the first intermediate of step 1 shows a structure similar to the reactant in step 1 with the following changes: the second carbon atom is an anion with a lone pair of electrons and is bonded to only one blue hydrogen. The second product is a blue ethanol. The first product undergoes a reversible chemical reaction in the presence of a compound whose structure shows a methyl group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methine group double bonded to a methylene group. A pink curved arrow is shown from the lone electron pair of the first intermediate of step 1 to the last carbon of the second compound; an arrow from the double bond between C3 and C4 points to C3. This reaction yields an intermediate whose structure shows a methyl group bonded to a carbonyl group (with pink oxygen) bonded to a methine group (carbon anion with a lone pair of electrons) bonded to a methylene group bonded (pink) to a carbon atom bonded to a blue hydrogen pink ethyl acetate and a carbonyl group (having pink oxygen) bonded to a methyl group. The supporting text in step 2 reads “The nucleophile adds to the alpha beta unsaturated ketone electrophile in a Michael reaction to generate a new enolate as product.” The final intermediate shown in step 2 undergoes a reversible reaction in the presence of blue ethoxide to yield 2 products in step 3. The structure of the first product shows a methyl group bonded to a carbonyl group (having pink oxygen) bonded to a methylene group (having 1 blue hydrogen) bonded to a methylene group bonded (pink) to a carbon atom bonded to a blue hydrogen pink ethyl acetate and a carbonyl group (having pink oxygen atom) bonded to a methyl group. The second product is a blue ethoxide anion. The supporting text in step 3 reads “The enolate product abstracts an acidic proton either from solvent or from starting keto ester to yield the final addition product.”">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_23_10_003.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption><emphasis effect="bold">Mechanism of the Michael reaction between a <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-keto ester and an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated ketone</emphasis>. The reaction is a conjugate addition of an enolate ion to the unsaturated carbonyl compound.</caption>
</figure>
<para id="para-00005">The Michael reaction occurs with a variety of <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated carbonyl compounds, not just conjugated ketones. Unsaturated aldehydes, esters, thioesters, nitriles, amides, and nitro compounds can all act as the electrophilic acceptor component in Michael reactions (<link target-id="table-00001"/>). Similarly, a variety of different donors can be used, including <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-diketones, <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-keto esters, malonic esters, <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-keto nitriles, and nitro compounds.</para>
<table id="table-00001" summary="An illustration (table) shows some Michael acceptors and Michael donors along with their structures: The compounds under Michael acceptors are as follows: Propenal with the structure showing a methylene group double bonded in pink to a methine group bonded to a methine group double bonded to an oxygen atom; 3-Buten-2-one with the structure showing a methylene bond double bonded in pink to a methine group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group; Ethyl propenoate with the structure showing a methylene group double bonded in pink to a methine group bonded to an acetate group bonded to ethyl group; Propenenitrile with the structure showing a methylene group double bonded in pink to a methine group bonded to a cyanide group; Nitroethylene with the structure showing a methylene group double bonded in pink to a methine group bonded to a nitro group. The compounds under Michael donors are as follows: beta Diketone with the structure showing a radical bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a blue methylene bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to R prime; beta Keto ester with the structure showing a radical group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a blue methylene group bonded to an acetate group bonded to an ethyl group; Diethyl malonate with the structure showing an ethyl group bonded to an acetate group bonded to a blue methylene group bonded to an acetate group bonded to an ethyl group; beta Keto nitrile with the structure showing a radical group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a blue methylene group bonded to a cyanide group; Nitro compound with the structure showing a radical group bonded to a blue methylene group bonded to a nitro group.">
