<example id="exam-00001">
<title>Using the Michael Reaction</title>
<para id="para-00006">How might you obtain the following compound using a Michael reaction?</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00004">
<media alt="An illustration shows a structure having a cyclohexanone having at its C2 an ethyl acetate and a line angle consisting of 3 carbon chain having an ethyl acetate at its terminal position">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_23_10_005.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00007"><title><span class="red-text">Strategy</span></title> A Michael reaction involves the conjugate addition of a stable enolate ion donor to an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated carbonyl acceptor, yielding a 1,5-dicarbonyl product. Usually, the stable enolate ion is derived from a <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-diketone, <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-keto ester, malonic ester, or similar compound. The C–C bond formed in the conjugate addition step is the one between the <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis> carbon of the acidic donor and the <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis> carbon of the unsaturated acceptor.</para>
<para id="para-00008"><title><span class="cyan-text">Solution</span></title></para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
<media alt="An illustration shows a chemical reaction between an enolate ion and an alpha beta-unsaturated carbonyl acceptor in the presence of sodium ethoxide and ethanol to yield a 1 5-dicarbonyl product. The structure of the enolate ion shows a cyclohexanone bonded at C2 to a hydrogen atom and a pink COOEt. C2 is labeled ‘alpha.’ The structure of alpha beta-unsaturated carbonyl acceptor (in blue) shows a methylene group (labeled beta) double bonded to a methine group (labeled alpha) bonded to COOEt. The structure of 1 5-dicarbonyl product shows a cyclohexanone bonded at C2 to a pink COOEt and a line angle structure containing a 3 carbon chain having a blue COOEt at its terminal position. C1-C2 bond of the line angle structure is in pink and labeled “This bond is formed in the Michael reaction.” C2 and C3 of the line angle structure is shown in blue.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_23_10_006.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
</example>
